Pre-Game Insights: England will be visited by Finland in the second round of the UEFA Nations League, League B on September 10, 2024.
The game will take place in Wembley Stadium in London, with a capacity of 90,000.
Denmark’s Krogh M. will be the referee for this match.
England wants to keep up momentum following a strong win, while Finland is trying to recover from a bad loss to Greece.
Both teams want to rank first in Group B2, making this match pivotal in the tournament.
England is the favorite with a better FIFA rating and an undefeated head-to-head performance against Finland in 11 past games.
Interim manager Lee Carsley has led England to a strong 2-0 triumph against the Republic of Ireland.
Finland has suffered in their most recent games, including a 3-0 loss to Greece.
England has traditionally dominated Finland, drawing two and winning nine of their eleven meetings.
Finland’s defense has been erratic, giving up three goals in several recent games.
England’s probable lineup includes Pickford (GK), Alexander-Arnold (DF), Guehi (DF), Maguire (DF), Colwill (DF), Mainoo (MF), Rice (MF), Grealish (MF), Saka (FW), Kane (FW), Gordon (FW).
Finland’s probable lineup includes Hradecky (GK), Stahl (DF), Hoskonen (DF), Ivanov (DF), Uronen (DF), Peltola (MF), Nissila (MF), Lod (MF), Kamara (MF), Antman (MF), Pohjanpalo (FW).
Key players injured for England include John Stones, Morgan Gibbs-White, and Ben Chilwell.
Key players injured for Finland include Kaan Kairinen and Rasmus Schuller.
Others: Harry Kane is set to make his 100th appearance for England.
Finland has conceded at least two goals in each of their last four away games.
Under Lee Carsley, England has shown more attacking freedom, registering more shots on target than under previous management.
England has failed to win their last three matches at Wembley.
Jack Grealish has been in fine form, contributing goals and assists in recent matches.
Finland has lost four of their last five away matches.
England has never lost to Finland in 11 meetings.
